00:53:27.050 --> 00:53:28.370
Who are some of the authors

00:53:28.370 --> 00:53:32.230
that have inspired
you in your writing?

00:53:32.230 --> 00:53:34.750
&gt;&gt; Becky Albertalli: So I, you
know, I think, I always say

00:53:34.750 --> 00:53:43.110
like there are two like books,
authors, who made me want

00:53:43.110 --> 00:53:48.490
to be a writer, or I think most
kind of influenced like the type

00:53:48.490 --> 00:53:49.790
of writing I like to do.

00:53:49.790 --> 00:53:55.420
One is Stephen Chbosky, like
The Perks of Being a Wallflower,

00:53:55.420 --> 00:53:57.950
which I read when I was like 16.

00:53:57.950 --> 00:54:01.460
And, you know, I was so in love

00:54:01.460 --> 00:54:02.990
with Charlie, the
main character.

00:54:02.990 --> 00:54:05.890
And I just, I felt
so connected to him.

00:54:05.890 --> 00:54:10.990
And the other author is an
Australian YA author named

00:54:10.990 --> 00:54:12.340
Jaclyn Moriarty.

00:54:12.340 --> 00:54:15.080
Actually, her sister is like
really famous right now.

00:54:15.080 --> 00:54:19.020
Like her sister is like
Liane Moriarty who writes

00:54:19.020 --> 00:54:21.470
like women's fiction
books that are huge.

00:54:21.470 --> 00:54:24.610
Is it like Big Little
Lies, I think?

00:54:24.610 --> 00:54:25.910
&gt;&gt; Roswell Encina:
That little movie.

00:54:25.910 --> 00:54:28.450
&gt;&gt; Becky Albertalli:
Yeah, well, I'm like a fan

00:54:28.450 --> 00:54:29.750
of her sister primarily.

00:54:29.750 --> 00:54:33.080
I actually like Liane's
books too a lot.

00:54:33.080 --> 00:54:35.980
Yeah, no, so her sister
has written this series

00:54:35.980 --> 00:54:40.000
of contemporary books
that, yeah, they take place

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:42.650
at like this high
school in Australia,

00:54:42.650 --> 00:54:45.620
and I think what I love about
them is similar to what I love

00:54:45.620 --> 00:54:47.330
about The Perks of Being
a Wallflower is just

00:54:47.330 --> 00:54:51.250
like these characters feel
so real, like they feel

00:54:51.250 --> 00:54:56.570
like actual people you could
know, and they, you know,

00:54:56.570 --> 00:55:01.560
and it doesn't feel like,
you know, the author tried

00:55:01.560 --> 00:55:04.900
to like infuse them
with quirks, you know,

00:55:04.900 --> 00:55:06.390
that would be memorable.

00:55:06.390 --> 00:55:10.190
Like it doesn't feel, like
you don't feel the craft

00:55:10.190 --> 00:55:11.610
when you read it.

00:55:11.610 --> 00:55:14.160
The craft is obviously there.

00:55:14.160 --> 00:55:20.190
But I think to me that's always
been my priority as a writer is

00:55:20.190 --> 00:55:25.380
to like make characters
who feel real.

00:55:25.380 --> 00:55:31.500
&gt;&gt; All right, so, hi, so I just
want to say that last year,

00:55:31.500 --> 00:55:33.170
Simon was like the
first book that I read

00:55:33.170 --> 00:55:36.050
that really got me back
into reading again.

00:55:36.050 --> 00:55:39.700
And even as like a 20-year-old
woman, I still could relate

00:55:39.700 --> 00:55:43.720
to a lot of the things
that Simon was like feeling

00:55:43.720 --> 00:55:46.160
from when I was like at that
point in my life where he was.

00:55:46.160 --> 00:55:50.690
And so I just want to say that
that book kind of inspired me

00:55:50.690 --> 00:55:52.050
to want to write my own book.

00:55:52.050 --> 00:55:56.000
So my question is, like,
what advice would you have

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:58.830
for somebody who would want to
write like a YA book one day?

00:55:58.830 --> 00:56:02.320
&gt;&gt; Becky Albertalli: So
I, I'm going to give kind

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:09.990
of my two favorite
pieces of advice.

00:56:09.990 --> 00:56:16.630
And I'm not-- and I should
kind of give the disclaimer

00:56:16.630 --> 00:56:22.310
that I don't have the
kind of like classical

00:56:22.310 --> 00:56:24.590
like writing training that
a lot of authors have.

00:56:24.590 --> 00:56:26.530
So I don't have an MFA.

00:56:26.530 --> 00:56:29.190
I don't know like bait
sheets and things like that.

00:56:29.190 --> 00:56:31.240
And there's things
like save the cat.

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:36.870
And I'm like, I love
cats, you know?

00:56:36.870 --> 00:56:42.900
So my most important piece of
advice is to write fan fiction

00:56:42.900 --> 00:56:48.450
because I think, because I think
it is the best writing practice

00:56:48.450 --> 00:56:49.820
out there.

00:56:49.820 --> 00:56:53.510
And not just because you're just
like actually like putting words

00:56:53.510 --> 00:56:56.360
on paper, but that is really,
really important to like just be

00:56:56.360 --> 00:56:58.050
like doing the thing,
getting used to doing it.

00:56:58.050 --> 00:57:02.890
But, you know, I think that
you are specifically trying

00:57:02.890 --> 00:57:07.530
to like aim for a voice, you
know, and like hit that target.

00:57:07.530 --> 00:57:11.970
And I think like when you
start to be able to like,

00:57:11.970 --> 00:57:17.850
to nail that with, you know,
existing characters, it becomes,

00:57:17.850 --> 00:57:21.310
like if you're trying to do
it with original characters,

00:57:21.310 --> 00:57:23.830
it's a different process,
but there's something

00:57:23.830 --> 00:57:25.130
about it that feels similar.

00:57:25.130 --> 00:57:27.580
Also, if you write like Leah
on the Offbeat, like the sequel

00:57:27.580 --> 00:57:31.120
in the same universe, it really
is like fan fiction, you know?

00:57:31.120 --> 00:57:32.590
Like pretty much, yeah.

00:57:32.590 --> 00:57:38.140
And then the other thing is
maybe even more important,

00:57:38.140 --> 00:57:42.330
which is like find your
community, you know,

00:57:42.330 --> 00:57:44.770
whether that's like
other authors,

00:57:44.770 --> 00:57:50.010
or just like bookish
people who are sort of going

00:57:50.010 --> 00:57:52.700
through some aspect of
the process with you.

00:57:52.700 --> 00:57:55.460
But like, you know, it
could be like a librarian

00:57:55.460 --> 00:57:57.520
or something like that.

00:57:57.520 --> 00:58:03.600
